<DOC><DOCNO> AP880702-0100 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1336EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-DefenseProbe-Chronology     07-02 0939</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Defense Probe-Chronology,940</SECOND><HEAD>How the Story Unfolded</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe-Justice</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here are major events in the investigation ofalleged procurement fraud and bribery involving governmentofficials, defense contractors and consultants:   JUNE 14: Pursuing what FBI spokesman Gregory Jones calls``allegations of fraud and bribery,'' FBI and Naval InvestigativeService agents raid the offices of Pentagon officials, defensecontractors and consultants.   More than 30 locations are searched in 12 states and theDistrict of Columbia. Law enforcement sources say the searches arepart of a two-year probe that has included wiretaps.   Targets include Melvyn Paisley, a former assistant Navysecretary who became a consultant to several aerospace contractorsimmediately upon leaving the Pentagon. Also searched are thePentagon offices of Victor Cohen, a top Air Force acquisitionsofficial, and James Gaines, deputy assistant Navy secretary foracquisitions, as well as offices and plants of some of thecountry's largest defense contractors, among them McDonnell DouglasCorp. in St. Louis, United Technologies Corp. in Washington andUnisys Corp. in Minneapolis and New York.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 16: A search warrant issued in the investigation statesthat McDonnell Douglas improperly received large amounts ofconfidential Pentagon information from Paisley. Law enforcementofficials say some 275 subpoenas have been served.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 17: Reps. Roy Dyson, D-Md., and Bill Chappell, D-Fla., denyreports that they are under scrutiny in the investigation. Two moredefense contractors _ LTV Corp. and Martin Marietta Corp. _acknowledge that they have been served with subpoenas.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 18: A second search warrant reveals that the FBI believesPratt andamp; Whitney obtained confidential documents that rival jetengine maker General Electric Co. had given to the DefenseDepartment in bidding for engine contracts worth hundreds ofmillions of dollars.   The warrant is used to search the offices of Eugene Tallia, vicepresident of Pratt andamp; Whitney and head of the company's Washingtonoffice.   Also reportedly under investigation are the activities of thelate Rep. Joseph Addabbo, D-N.Y., who was chairman of the HouseAppropriations defense subcommittee.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 20: Three other congressmen _ Rep. Thomas Downey, D-N.Y.,Andrew Ireland, R-Fla., and Sam Stratton, D-N.Y. _ are reported onthe list of those under scrutiny, but not targets, in the case.   Three more defense contractors: Hercules Inc., Gould Inc. andthe Electronic Data Systems Corp., say they have been served withsubpoenas.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 21: Pentagon spokesmen say Defense Secretary Frank C.Carlucci has issued a directive specifying that any Pentagonemployee under scrutiny in the bribery probe must be reassigned.   President Reagan, in a news conference in Toronto at the end ofthe economic summit, said he was ``very upset'' about reports ofwrongdoing. But he praised investigators for ferreting out themisdeeds and said it was ``understandable how such things'' couldhappen in a government bureaucracy.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 22: House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, says after a meetingwith the prosecutor in the Pentagon probe that ``no member of theHouse is under investigation'' in the case.   Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger, in an interview,denies responsibilty for whatever corruption may be found. ``Nomatter how careful you are, you're not going to be able toeliminate dishonesty,'' he says.   BDM International Inc. of McLean, Va., is reported to have beenserved with a subpoena. Paisley's wife, Vicki, is an employee ofthe company.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 23: The Los Angeles Times reports that investigatorsbelieve Gaines was a principal supplier of Pentagon documents toPaisley. The newspaper says Paisley allegedly passed theinformation to McDonnell Douglas, which paid him ``staggeringfees.'' An attorney for Paisley denies the allegations.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 24: The Senate Armed Services Committee considerslegislation to allow the government to suspend payments to defensecontractors under investigation in the case. Sen. Ted Stevens,R-Alaska, offered the proposal but later withdrew it.  </TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 26: Sources say investigators videotaped meetings in whichDefense Department officials allegedly took payoffs fromconsultants. The sources say Gaines and Cohen appear on some of thevideotapes, as does Paisley.   The Washington Post, meanwhile, reports that Cohen iscooperating in the investigation.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 27 _ Carlucci says the government may terminate as many as100 contracts suspected of being tainted in the investigation intoalleged fraud and bribery. However, Carlucci warns againstprematurely condemning and abandoning the entire procurement systembefore ``all the facts are in.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 28 _ Justice Department officials acknowledge that AttorneyGeneral Edwin Meese III recused himself from the Pentagon fraudinvestigation a day earlier because his own defense lawyers arerepresenting clients involved in the case.   The Associated Press obtains a copy of a May 5 memo written byRobert Costello, undersecretary of defense for acquisition, toCarlucci suggesting that top Pentagon officials be given veto powerover searches of contractor facilities.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 29 _ Henry Hudson, the U.S. attorney heading theinvestigation, says in court papers that he has learned of severalinstances of documents being destroyed by people underinvestigation in the probe. No details were given on who destroyeddocuments or how they may have related to the investigation.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JUNE 30 _ Court documents unsealed in federal court in Dallasreveal that FBI agents eavesdropped as a Navy procurement official,George Stone, read to a private defense consultant the sealed bidsfrom 10 companies competing for a $120 million air controlcontract. Stone is one of six Pentagon officials transferred toother duties after their offices were searched.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><TEXT>   JULY 1 _ Carlucci announces that he is acting on information inthe documents unsealed in Dallas by suspending payments on $1billion worth of contracts.</TEXT></DOC>